<section xml:id="sec-review0421">
  <title>Continuity and Uniform Continuity</title>
  
  <p>We've built on our understanding of functional limits to establish the concept of continuity and some of its consequences:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          What it means for a function to be continuous on a set.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          What is means for a function to be uniformly continuous on a set.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The algebraic combination of continuous functions and the composition of continuous functions are also continuous.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The image of a compact set under a continuous function is also compact.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          A continuous function on a compact domain attains both an absolute maximum value and an absolute minimum value.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          A function that is continuous at every point of a compact set is uniformly continuous on that compact set.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>

  <p>
    I also mentioned without proof the following consequences of continuity:
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>E \subset \mathbb{R}</m> is a connected set, and if <m>f:E \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> is continuous on <m>E</m> then <m>f(E)</m> is a connected set.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          If <m>f:\mathbb{R} \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> is continuous on <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, and if <m>B \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m> is an open set, then <m>f^{-1}(B)</m> is an open set.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </p>
  <p> 
    The first of these gives us ...
  </p>

  <theorem xml:id="thm-ivt">
    <title>Intermediate Value Theorem</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        If <m>f:[a,b] \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>, and if <m>L</m> is any number between <m>f(a)</m> and <m>f(b)</m>, then there is a <m>c \in [a,b]</m> at which <m>f(c)=L</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </theorem>
  
  <p>
    This is a very important consequence of the completeness of the reals.
  </p>
</section>

<section xml:id="sec-diff">
  <title>Differentiability</title>
  
  <p>
    In Calculus 1, we learn about the property of differentiability, what it says about functions, and how it can be used to learn other things about functions and to model real-world phenomena.
  </p>

  <definition xml:id="def-diffbl">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>g : A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> be a function on an interval <m>A \subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.  Given <m>c \in A</m>, the <term>derivative of <m>g</m> at <m>c</m></term> is defined by
        <md>
          <mrow>g'(c) \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow c} \frac{g(x)-x(c)}{x-c} \amp </mrow>
        </md>
        provided the limit exists.  In this case we say <term><m>g</m> is differentiable at <m>x=c</m></term>.  If <m>g'</m> exists for all points <m>c \in A</m>, we say that <term><m>g</m> is differentiable on <m>A</m></term>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>


</section>

<theorem xml:id="thm-diffcts">
  <title>Differentiablity implies Continuity</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>f(x)</m> is differentiable at <m>x=c</m>, then <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>x=c</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p>
  This means that continuity is prerequisite for differentiability.  (The contrapositive of the above.)
</p>

<proof>
  <p>
    Suppose that <m>f</m> is differentiable at <m>x=c</m>.  This means that the following limit exists and is finite:
    <md>
          <mrow>\lim_{x \rightarrow c} \frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} \amp = f'(c)</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
</proof>
